---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Bus Service Frequency Changes in Tel Aviv: 2022–2024"
  year="2024"
  category="Public Transport Analysis · Temporal GIS"
  tools={['Python', 'GTFS', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Choropleth Mapping']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        How often a bus arrives is one of the clearest measures of transit quality — an 8-minute
        headway versus a 20-minute one is the difference between a service people rely on and one
        they plan around. This project tracked how Tel Aviv's bus frequency shifted between 2022
        and 2024, and where.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Year-over-Year Frequency Change</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2022-2023.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency changes in Tel Aviv between 2022 and 2023"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2022 → 2023: Route segments colored by change in service frequency. Green = improved headways; red = reduced frequency.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2023-2024.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency changes in Tel Aviv between 2023 and 2024"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2023 → 2024: Continued restructuring as light rail integration proceeded, with frequency gains on trunk corridors.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/freq-2024.jpg`}
      alt="Map of bus service frequency in Tel Aviv, 2024"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      2024 state: Current service frequency baseline across the network.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Processed three years of <strong>GTFS</strong> feeds in <strong>Python</strong> to compute average headways by route segment and time period (AM/PM peak, off-peak).</li>
      <li>Matched segments across years by route ID and calculated year-over-year change in headway as the core metric.</li>
      <li>Joined GTFS route geometries to the computed deltas with <strong>GeoPandas</strong>, then built diverging <strong>choropleth maps</strong> in <strong>QGIS</strong> centered on zero change.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        The maps surfaced both citywide trends and localized shifts tied to specific
        restructurings — most notably the new light rail integration, which absorbed bus demand on
        some corridors while boosting frequency on connecting trunk routes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }
</style>
